<div class="lobby">
  <div class="lobby-card">
    <h1>WebRTC + Action Cable</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">
      A live demo of peer-to-peer video using WebRTC for media and
      Action Cable (WebSockets) for signaling.
    </p>

    <form class="room-form" onsubmit="joinRoom(event)">
      <label for="room-name">Room name</label>
      <input
        id="room-name"
        type="text"
        placeholder="e.g. my-room"
        required
        autocomplete="off"
        autofocus
      >
      <button type="submit">Join Room &rarr;</button>
    </form>

    <div class="how-it-works">
      <h2>How it works</h2>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <strong>Action Cable (WebSocket)</strong> — When you join a room, your
          browser opens a persistent WebSocket connection to the Rails server via
          <code>SignalingChannel</code>. This channel relays small "signaling"
          messages (SDP offers/answers and ICE candidates) between peers.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>WebRTC</strong> — Once both peers have exchanged signaling
          messages, the browser establishes a direct peer-to-peer media connection.
          Audio and video then flow <em>directly</em> between browsers — the Rails
          server is no longer involved.
        </li>
      </ol>
      <p class="tip">
        Open this room on two different browsers or machines on the same network
        and enter the same room name to connect.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<script>
  function joinRoom(e) {
    e.preventDefault()
    const name = document.getElementById("room-name").value.trim()
    if (name) window.location.href = "/rooms/" + encodeURIComponent(name)
  }
</script>
